<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="38" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="37.[151,1437,860,1319]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,860,886]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Slender insects, white with black spots, translucent tegmina with brown or black spots in most species (
<figureCitation box="[159,261,896,922]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1114,1138]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,310,1090]" captionTargetId="figure-80@38.[151,1436,309,1091]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 22. Quiva species. A–D. Q. (P.) angieae. E–H. Q. (Q.) pulchella. I–K. Q. (Q.) diaphana. L–N. Q. (Q.) buhrnheimi. O–Q. Q. (Q.) sharovi. R–T. Q. (Q.) abacata. U–W. Q. (Q.) gutjahrae. A, E. Male habitus in lateral view. B, F, I, L, O, R, U. Frons. C, G, J, M, P, S, V. Subgenital plates. D, H, K, N, Q, T, W. Cerci." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876267/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Fig. 22E</figureCitation>
), except for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cadena-Castaneda" authorityYear="2013" box="[399,522,896,922]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Quiva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angieae">
<emphasis box="[399,522,896,922]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Q. angieae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with black tegmina (
<figureCitation box="[758,863,896,922]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1114,1138]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,310,1090]" captionTargetId="figure-80@38.[151,1436,309,1091]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 22. Quiva species. A–D. Q. (P.) angieae. E–H. Q. (Q.) pulchella. I–K. Q. (Q.) diaphana. L–N. Q. (Q.) buhrnheimi. O–Q. Q. (Q.) sharovi. R–T. Q. (Q.) abacata. U–W. Q. (Q.) gutjahrae. A, E. Male habitus in lateral view. B, F, I, L, O, R, U. Frons. C, G, J, M, P, S, V. Subgenital plates. D, H, K, N, Q, T, W. Cerci." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876267/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Fig. 22A</figureCitation>
). Vertex smooth, not distinctly elevated at the fastigium, rounded and curved, ending in a blunt tooth, a little separated from the fastigium of the frons. Face rounded without lateral carinae (
<figureCitation box="[425,596,968,995]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1114,1138]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,310,1090]" captionTargetId="figure-80@38.[151,1436,309,1091]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 22. Quiva species. A–D. Q. (P.) angieae. E–H. Q. (Q.) pulchella. I–K. Q. (Q.) diaphana. L–N. Q. (Q.) buhrnheimi. O–Q. Q. (Q.) sharovi. R–T. Q. (Q.) abacata. U–W. Q. (Q.) gutjahrae. A, E. Male habitus in lateral view. B, F, I, L, O, R, U. Frons. C, G, J, M, P, S, V. Subgenital plates. D, H, K, N, Q, T, W. Cerci." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876267/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Figs. 22B, F, I</figureCitation>
). Tegmina very narrow, medial vein with two branches connected to the cubital vein by a short vein. Fore femur with two spinules on external genicular lobe, dorsal margin of fore tibiae unarmed except for a single apical, lateral spine. Hind femur with basal half of its length thickened, then narrowed abruptly into thin distal half. Ventral margin of hind femur armed with small spinules, in the same way as the dorsal margin of the hind tibiae (
<figureCitation box="[448,597,1112,1138]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1114,1138]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,310,1090]" captionTargetId="figure-80@38.[151,1436,309,1091]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 22. Quiva species. A–D. Q. (P.) angieae. E–H. Q. (Q.) pulchella. I–K. Q. (Q.) diaphana. L–N. Q. (Q.) buhrnheimi. O–Q. Q. (Q.) sharovi. R–T. Q. (Q.) abacata. U–W. Q. (Q.) gutjahrae. A, E. Male habitus in lateral view. B, F, I, L, O, R, U. Frons. C, G, J, M, P, S, V. Subgenital plates. D, H, K, N, Q, T, W. Cerci." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876267/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Figs. 22A, E</figureCitation>
). Male cerci with a small internal triangular spine, outer branch elongated (
<figureCitation box="[159,336,1148,1174]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1114,1138]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,310,1090]" captionTargetId="figure-80@38.[151,1436,309,1091]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 22. Quiva species. A–D. Q. (P.) angieae. E–H. Q. (Q.) pulchella. I–K. Q. (Q.) diaphana. L–N. Q. (Q.) buhrnheimi. O–Q. Q. (Q.) sharovi. R–T. Q. (Q.) abacata. U–W. Q. (Q.) gutjahrae. A, E. Male habitus in lateral view. B, F, I, L, O, R, U. Frons. C, G, J, M, P, S, V. Subgenital plates. D, H, K, N, Q, T, W. Cerci." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876267/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Figs. 22H, Q, T</figureCitation>
), and with an apical spine, except 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cadena-Castaneda" authorityYear="2013" box="[715,837,1148,1174]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Quiva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angieae">
<emphasis box="[715,837,1148,1174]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Q. angieae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[851,955,1148,1174]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1114,1138]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,310,1090]" captionTargetId="figure-80@38.[151,1436,309,1091]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 22. Quiva species. A–D. Q. (P.) angieae. E–H. Q. (Q.) pulchella. I–K. Q. (Q.) diaphana. L–N. Q. (Q.) buhrnheimi. O–Q. Q. (Q.) sharovi. R–T. Q. (Q.) abacata. U–W. Q. (Q.) gutjahrae. A, E. Male habitus in lateral view. B, F, I, L, O, R, U. Frons. C, G, J, M, P, S, V. Subgenital plates. D, H, K, N, Q, T, W. Cerci." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876267/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Fig. 22D</figureCitation>
). Male subgenital plate elongate with small styli. (
<figureCitation box="[223,411,1184,1211]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1114,1138]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,310,1090]" captionTargetId="figure-80@38.[151,1436,309,1091]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 22. Quiva species. A–D. Q. (P.) angieae. E–H. Q. (Q.) pulchella. I–K. Q. (Q.) diaphana. L–N. Q. (Q.) buhrnheimi. O–Q. Q. (Q.) sharovi. R–T. Q. (Q.) abacata. U–W. Q. (Q.) gutjahrae. A, E. Male habitus in lateral view. B, F, I, L, O, R, U. Frons. C, G, J, M, P, S, V. Subgenital plates. D, H, K, N, Q, T, W. Cerci." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876267/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Figs. 22G, M, V</figureCitation>
) Ovipositor as long as pronotum, slightly curved, margins from mesal to distal region serrulate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,982,1256,1282]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" type="type_taxon">
<paragraph blockId="37.[151,1437,860,1319]" box="[199,982,1256,1282]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,354,1256,1282]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
