<emphasis bold="true" box="[998,1101,1456,1477]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Paraquiva</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1114,1191,1456,1477]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">angieae</emphasis>
</emphasis>
Cadena-Castañeda, 2013 Tegmina
</taxonomicName>
with large membranous cells in costal area and with distal part of MA connected by a short vein with Rs before Rs bifurcation (
<figureCitation box="[344,430,1515,1537]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1114,1138]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,310,1090]" captionTargetId="figure-80@38.[151,1436,309,1091]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 22. Quiva species. A–D. Q. (P.) angieae. E–H. Q. (Q.) pulchella. I–K. Q. (Q.) diaphana. L–N. Q. (Q.) buhrnheimi. O–Q. Q. (Q.) sharovi. R–T. Q. (Q.) abacata. U–W. Q. (Q.) gutjahrae. A, E. Male habitus in lateral view. B, F, I, L, O, R, U. Frons. C, G, J, M, P, S, V. Subgenital plates. D, H, K, N, Q, T, W. Cerci." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876267/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 22E</figureCitation>
); male cerci with outer branch distinctly longer than inner branch (
<figureCitation box="[1064,1216,1515,1537]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1114,1138]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,310,1090]" captionTargetId="figure-80@38.[151,1436,309,1091]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 22. Quiva species. A–D. Q. (P.) angieae. E–H. Q. (Q.) pulchella. I–K. Q. (Q.) diaphana. L–N. Q. (Q.) buhrnheimi. O–Q. Q. (Q.) sharovi. R–T. Q. (Q.) abacata. U–W. Q. (Q.) gutjahrae. A, E. Male habitus in lateral view. B, F, I, L, O, R, U. Frons. C, G, J, M, P, S, V. Subgenital plates. D, H, K, N, Q, T, W. Cerci." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876267/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Figs. 22K, Q, T</figureCitation>
); male subgenital plate with very short styli and rather deep emargination between them (
<figureCitation box="[858,1018,1544,1566]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1114,1138]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,310,1090]" captionTargetId="figure-80@38.[151,1436,309,1091]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 22. Quiva species. A–D. Q. (P.) angieae. E–H. Q. (Q.) pulchella. I–K. Q. (Q.) diaphana. L–N. Q. (Q.) buhrnheimi. O–Q. Q. (Q.) sharovi. R–T. Q. (Q.) abacata. U–W. Q. (Q.) gutjahrae. A, E. Male habitus in lateral view. B, F, I, L, O, R, U. Frons. C, G, J, M, P, S, V. Subgenital plates. D, H, K, N, Q, T, W. Cerci." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876267/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Figs. 22G, M, V</figureCitation>
)........................ 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1310,1407,1544,1566]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hebard" authorityYear="1927" box="[1310,1370,1544,1565]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Quiva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">Quiva</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1376,1407,1545,1566]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" sensu="stricto">s.s.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
...2
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1437,1398,2036]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
2. Outer branch of male cerci with almost truncate apex having much thinner apical spine; inner branch very short, much shorter than outer branch (
<figureCitation box="[407,565,1603,1625]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1114,1138]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,310,1090]" captionTargetId="figure-80@38.[151,1436,309,1091]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 22. Quiva species. A–D. Q. (P.) angieae. E–H. Q. (Q.) pulchella. I–K. Q. (Q.) diaphana. L–N. Q. (Q.) buhrnheimi. O–Q. Q. (Q.) sharovi. R–T. Q. (Q.) abacata. U–W. Q. (Q.) gutjahrae. A, E. Male habitus in lateral view. B, F, I, L, O, R, U. Frons. C, G, J, M, P, S, V. Subgenital plates. D, H, K, N, Q, T, W. Cerci." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876267/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Figs. 22H, K, N</figureCitation>
)....................................................... 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1233,1400,1603,1625]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Diaphana group</emphasis>
...3 Outer branch of male cerci with more or less gradually narrowing distal part (apical part of this branch insignificantly narrower than its remaining part); inner branch of cerci of diverse length (
<figureCitation box="[843,1000,1662,1684]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1114,1138]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,310,1090]" captionTargetId="figure-80@38.[151,1436,309,1091]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 22. Quiva species. A–D. Q. (P.) angieae. E–H. Q. (Q.) pulchella. I–K. Q. (Q.) diaphana. L–N. Q. (Q.) buhrnheimi. O–Q. Q. (Q.) sharovi. R–T. Q. (Q.) abacata. U–W. Q. (Q.) gutjahrae. A, E. Male habitus in lateral view. B, F, I, L, O, R, U. Frons. C, G, J, M, P, S, V. Subgenital plates. D, H, K, N, Q, T, W. Cerci." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876267/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Figs. 22Q, T, W</figureCitation>
).................... 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1254,1406,1662,1683]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Abacata group</emphasis>
...5
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1437,1398,2036]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
